<ArticleLayout
  title="TV and Media Storage That Keeps Cables Reachable"
  description="Choose a TV or media unit that fits the screen, devices and walking space while keeping ventilation, cables and power connections reachable."
  category="Living Spaces"
  faqs={faqs}
  date="Updated July 2026"
  dateModified="2026-07-23"
  readingTime="9 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/living-room.webp"
  imageAlt="A warm living room with a TV unit, tidy media storage and soft natural light"
>
  <p>
    A media unit is rarely used with only a television. The soundbar needs a clear line, consoles need
    ventilation, cables must reach power and somebody eventually has to clean behind everything.
  </p>
  <p>
    Map the screen, devices and connection points before choosing furniture. Mark the unit, open
    doors and drawers on the floor, and leave every cable reachable. Closed storage only calms the
    room when it does not trap heat or make routine access difficult.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure the Actual Screen and Stand</h2>
  <p>
    Advertised screen size is diagonal and does not reveal the television's width. Measure the whole
    set and note whether it uses widely spaced feet or a central stand. Every support point must sit
    fully on a surface designed for the television and within the unit's stated load.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure the available wall, viewing position and routes to doors or balconies. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/sofa-and-seating-layout-what-to-measure-before-buying-furniture/">sofa and seating layout guide</a>{" "}
    helps coordinate the viewing zone, while the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-rug-size-and-placement-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">living room rug guide</a>{" "}
    covers floor edges near drawers and walkways.
  </p>

  <h2>List Every Device and Connection</h2>
  <p>
    Record the dimensions of the soundbar, console, router, streaming box, speakers, charging dock
    and any older player that will remain. Measure again with plugs attached: HDMI and power leads
    need bending room behind a device that otherwise appears to fit.
  </p>
  <p>
    Note power, antenna and data points before placing the unit. A cable opening is useful only when
    it aligns with the shelf and connection. Do not hide a power point so completely that plugs and
    power boards cannot be inspected or disconnected.
  </p>

  <h2>Mark the Furniture in Use</h2>
  <p>
    Tape the unit's width and depth on the floor, then add the full swing of cupboards and extension
    of drawers. Walk between the sofa, coffee table, unit and nearby door. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/side-tables-coffee-tables-and-console-tables-what-to-compare-before-you-buy/">living room tables guide</a>{" "}
    can help if several pieces compete for the same clearance.
  </p>
  <p>
    Long consoles balance a broad wall and can overwhelm an apartment. Compact or corner units save
    space and reduce future layout options. A floating unit may look lighter but requires suitable
    structure, fixings, installation and rental approval.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose Open or Closed Storage by Device</h2>
  <p>
    Open shelves keep frequently used electronics accessible and expose their cables. Drawers suit
    controllers, remotes and manuals; cupboards hide visual clutter but can interfere with signals,
    controls, ventilation and connection access.
  </p>
  <p>
    Follow each device maker's clearance and ventilation instructions. Do not assume a cable hole is
    adequate ventilation or run equipment inside a closed compartment merely because it fits. Keep
    remote and controller reset points simple; the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/toy-blanket-and-everyday-clutter-control-for-living-rooms/">living room clutter control guide</a>{" "}
    covers the surrounding toys, blankets and pet items.
  </p>

  <h2>Protect Cable and Power Access</h2>
  <p>
    Leave enough slack for equipment to be moved without pulling a connection, while keeping cords
    out of walking routes. Do not crush cables behind furniture, cover power boards or overload them.
    Fixed electrical work and in-wall cable routing require appropriately qualified help.
  </p>
  <p>
    Cable sleeves and boxes should still allow inspection, cleaning and future device changes. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-cable-management-what-to-plan-before-buying-organisers/">living room cable management guide</a>{" "}
    provides a detailed map of devices and power points. If lamps or screen reflections complicate the layout,
    see the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-lighting-ideas-for-australian-homes/">living room lighting guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Secure the Television and Furniture</h2>
  <p>
    Entertainment units of any height are covered by Australia's toppling-furniture mandatory
    information standard. Look for the required warnings and follow the supplied anchoring guidance.
    A television should sit on furniture designed for it and be secured as directed.
  </p>
  <p>
    The{" "}
    <a href="https://www.productsafety.gov.au/consumers/be-safe-around-the-home/use-products-inside-the-home-safely/toppling-furniture-and-televisions-guide" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ACCC guide to toppling furniture and televisions</a>{" "}
    explains how opening doors and drawers affects stability and why both the TV and supporting
    furniture may need securing. Keep heavy items low and do not place objects that encourage
    children to climb on top. Renters should discuss anchoring with the landlord or agent.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan the Everyday Storage</h2>
  <p>
    Give remotes, batteries and controllers a shallow drawer, tray or basket. Avoid filling device
    shelves with unrelated household overflow. Our{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-storage-ideas-everyday-australian-homes/">living room storage guide</a>{" "}
    helps divide media storage from books, toys and general clutter.
  </p>
  <p>
    Open shelving and electronics collect dust. Choose a unit that allows a vacuum or cloth to reach
    behind cables and beneath the base without repeatedly disconnecting everything. Slatted doors and
    textured finishes may add ventilation or visual interest and require more detailed cleaning.
  </p>

  <h2>Check the Complete Media Setup</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Measure the television, feet and total load.</li>
    <li>Measure devices with their plugs and cables attached.</li>
    <li>Mark doors, drawers, walkways and cleaning access.</li>
    <li>Keep power points and cable connections reachable.</li>
    <li>Follow device clearance and ventilation instructions.</li>
    <li>Plan compliant anchoring for the unit and television.</li>
    <li>Obtain approval before permanent work in a rental.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A simple unit that fits the TV, devices and room will usually outlast an elaborate cabinet built
    around today's equipment. Preserve access, ventilation and stability first. Browse the{" "}
    <a href="/categories/living-spaces/">Living Spaces</a>{" "}
    category and our{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-storage-ideas-everyday-australian-homes/">living room storage guide</a>{" "}
    for the wider room.
  </p>

  <RelatedGuidesBlock guides={relatedGuides} />
</ArticleLayout>
